#!/bin/bash
# Script 5: VLC Open Source Manifesto Generator
# Author: Aastha Krishna

echo "======================================"
echo " VLC Open Source Manifesto Generator "
echo "======================================"
echo "Answer three questions to generate your manifesto."
echo ""

read -p "1. Name one multimedia tool you use often: " TOOL
read -p "2. In one word, what does 'open source freedom' mean to you? " FREEDOM
read -p "3. Name one media project you would share freely: " BUILD

DATE=$(date '+%d %B %Y')
USER_NAME="aastha"
OUTPUT="vlc_manifesto_${USER_NAME}.txt"

# Compose manifesto using the answers
cat << EOF > "$OUTPUT"
--- The VLC Open Source Manifesto ---
Date: $DATE
Author: Aastha Krishna

As a technology enthusiast, I rely on tools developed by global open-source communities. 
Applications like VLC Media Player and $TOOL show how collaboration can create powerful tools that are accessible to everyone.

To me, freedom means $FREEDOM. It means the ability to explore, modify, and improve technology without restrictions. 
Open-source multimedia platforms such as VLC prove that innovation grows faster when knowledge is shared.

If I could contribute something to the open-source world, I would create $BUILD and release it freely so others can learn, improve it, and build upon it.

Open source is not just software—it is a philosophy of sharing, learning, and community.
EOF

echo ""
echo "Manifesto successfully saved to $OUTPUT"
echo "======================================"
cat "$OUTPUT"
